[1] Southern Africa: epidemic expansion
Date: Fri 7 Jan 2022
Source: Nature [abridged, edited]
https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-021-03832-5


Citation. Viana R, Moyo S, Amoako DG, et al. Rapid epidemic expansion of the SARS-CoV-2 omicron variant in southern Africa. Nature 2022; research briefing
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) epidemic in southern Africa has been characterised by 3 distinct waves. The 1st was associated with a mix of SARS-CoV-2 lineages, whilst the 2nd and 3rd waves were driven by the beta and delta variants, respectively (1-3). In November 2021, genomic surveillance teams in South Africa and Botswana detected a new SARS-CoV-2 variant associated with a rapid resurgence of infections in Gauteng Province, South Africa. Within 3 days of the 1st genome being uploaded, it was designated a variant of concern (omicron) by the World Health Organization and, within 3 weeks, had been identified in 87 countries. The omicron variant is exceptional for carrying over 30 mutations in the spike glycoprotein, predicted to influence antibody neutralization and spike function. Here, we describe the genomic profile and early transmission dynamics of omicron, highlighting the rapid spread in regions with high levels of population immunity.

--
