[3] Mexico: cases
Date: Thu 6 Jan 2022
Source: NBC News, Reuters report [edited]
https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/mexico-likely-surpass-300k-COVID-19-deaths-week-fifth-highest-worldwid-rcna11176


Mexico is likely to surpass 300 000 deaths from COVID-19 this week -- the 5th highest death toll worldwide -- as infections rise after the holiday season, fueled by the omicron coronavirus variant and largely unrestricted tourism.

Infections have more than doubled to 20 000 during the last week when many US tourists visited Mexico. 11 of Mexico's 32 states decided not to resume in-person school classes this week with cases climbing fast.

The arrival of the highly contagious omicron variant reversed a downturn in infections during the autumn [2021] when the widespread application of vaccines provided relief.

Some Mexicans said people had dropped their guard as the holidays came. "Since December [2021], a lot of people started to go out and there are many who no longer wear face masks," said Isauro Perez, a 53-year-old taxi driver in Mexico City. "If we don't take care of ourselves, the government won't take care of us."

As of Wed [5 Jan 2022], Mexico had registered 299 805 confirmed deaths from COVID-19, a figure that is likely significantly below the real toll, officials say.

Separate government data showed there had been nearly 452 000 deaths "linked to" COVID-19 by mid-December [2021], and lower testing has likely helped to understate the reach of the virus.

Mexico has the highest fatality rate -- deaths per confirmed cases -- among the 20 nations most affected by COVID-19 worldwide, according to an analysis by Johns Hopkins University.

Laurie Ximenez-Fyvie, an expert on molecular genetics at the National Autonomous University of Mexico (UNAM), said in the end, Mexico's death toll would be the ultimate yardstick of how the government had performed in the pandemic.

So far, she argued, it risked suffering "absolute failure."

--
