[7] Global update: Worldometer accessed 8 Jan 2022 20:05 EST (GMT-5)
Date: Fri 7 Jan 2022
Source: Worldometer [edited]
https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries


Total number of reported deaths: 5 502 666
Total number of worldwide cases: 306 037 922
Number of newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours: 2 256 866

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[For those who wish to see the detailed global data, a snapshot of the Worldometer table at the time we accessed it is available at https://promedmail.org/wp-content/uploads/world-pdf/2022%20WORLDDATA%20JUNE8_1641788178.pdf.

A 7-day series of cumulative data reported by countries, territories, and reporting entities can be found at https://promedmail.org/wp-content/uploads/world-pdf/2022%20JAN8WORLD7_1641788189.pdf. Mod.UBA]

In the past 24 hours, 28 countries including the USA (489 602), France (303 669), Spain (242 440), Italy (197 535), India (160 244), the UK (140 566), Argentina (101 689), Australia (93 309), Turkey (66 237), Brazil (49 303), Germany (42 422), Canada (41 723), Greece (37 670), Portugal (35 643), Colombia (31 170), Mexico (30 671), the Netherlands (27 890), Belgium (24 694), Philippines (26 211), Ireland (26 122), Israel (22 398), Bolivia (19 013), Russia (16 568), Viet Nam (16 553), Japan (13 913), Peru (12 833), Denmark (11 604), and Poland (10 897), reported the highest numbers of cases, all reporting more than 10 000 newly confirmed cases. A global total of 5618 deaths were reported in the preceding 24 hours (late 6 Jan to late 7 Jan 2022). The exponential rise in cases over the last couple of weeks can be attributed to the rapid increase in the omicron variant cases in over 90 countries. Studies suggest that the omicron variant causes milder disease than the previously dominant delta variant, but the high number of cases caused by this highly infectious/transmissible variant could rapidly overwhelm hospitals and health systems. The 7-day averages indicate an increasing global trend for cases and deaths.

A total of 72 countries reported more than 1000 cases in the past 24 hours; 39 of the 75 countries are from the European region, 8 are from the Americas region, 5 are from the Western Pacific region, 6 are from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 3 from the South East Asia region, and 11 are from the African region.

Comparing the 7-day averages of daily confirmed cases from the past 7 days and those from 8-14 days ago, case counts have increased by 65.1%, while daily reported deaths have increased by 2.5%. Similar comparative 7-day averages in the USA show a 79.3% increase in daily reported cases and a 26.6% increase in reported deaths.

Impression: Globally, more than 2 200 000 newly confirmed infections were reported in the past 24 hours with over 306.03 million cumulative reported cases and over 5.50 million reported deaths. - Mod.UBA]
